article.description: Brandon Jenkins scored a career-high 31 points to lead Louisville to a 81-58 win over UC Davis on Monday night.
article.headline: Jenkins hits 11 of 13 shots, scores career-high 31
article.linkText: Louisville's Jenkins fills in for Dean, pours in 31 points
article.story: LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Brandon Jenkins ran to the right corner, took the pass from a Louisville teammate and let it fly. Behind him, Louisville guard Taquan Dean stood up from his spot at the end of the bench with both arms in the air, ready to celebrate Jenkins' eighth 3-pointer of the night. Clang. The hit the back of the rim and fell away. Dean dropped his arms in surprise. The way Jenkins shot the ball during No. 10 Louisville's 81-58 win over visiting UC Davis, you couldn't blame Dean for getting a little ahead of himself. Jenkins scored a career-high 31 points while filling in admirably for the injured Dean as the Cardinals (13-2) overwhelmed the overmatched Aggies (4-10). Jenkins made 11 of 13 shots from the field, including 7-of-9 from 3-point range to make sure the Cardinals survived without Dean, their captain and leading scorer. "It felt comfortable shooting," said Jenkins, who turned 21 on Sunday. "I felt it during shootaround and after I made a couple, it really felt good. Guys were making the extra pass and I couldn't believe how open I was." The Cardinals picked apart whatever defense UC Davis threw at them. The Cardinals shot 55 percent from the floor, including 67 percent in the first half. "I loved the unselfishness," said Louisville coach Rick Pitino. "I asked the young guys to play like a mature basketball team with Taquan out and not try to do too much and they did that." Dean suffered a sprained ankle in Louisville's win at Providence last Saturday, and spent the night cheering on his teammates while Jenkins stepped in and did his best Dean impression. "You got to see the real Brandon tonight," said Louisville guard Terrence Williams. "He's an All-American behind closed doors. I told him tonight with Taquan being out, 'It's you.' " UC Davis coach Gary Stewart joked maybe his players were a little too busy studying Dean's immaculate black suit than guarding Dean. "I think we spent a lot of time looking at Taquan over there on the bench in street clothes instead of focusing on Brandon. He had a terrific night." He wasn't alone. David Padgett finished with 14 points while Williams added eight points, eight rebounds and eight assists for Louisville. "Every game we're just trying, it seems, to do something better," Padgett said. "Once we piece it all together, I think we'll be a pretty good team." Kyle Brucculeri led the Aggies with 15 points, but UC Davis, a provisional member of Division I, could not find the magic that helped it upset Stanford on the road earlier this season. "We didn't want to take them lightly," Jenkins said. "We knew what they'd done." Pitino planned to use his team's final non-conference game of the regular season to create a little chaos with the press. Injuries and lack of practice time have forced the Cardinals to phase in the variety of presses and traps a little later in the season than usual. Against the Aggies the Cardinals used full-court pressure until long after the game was decided. Though Louisville didn't exactly cause the Aggies to panic -- UC Davis turned it over 16 times, just above its season average -- the Cardinals were able to push the tempo and get out on the break with ease. With No. 12 Pittsburgh coming to Freedom Hall on Sunday, Pitino saw enough to be optimistic the relatively young and inexperienced Cardinals can hang with some of the bigger, brawnier teams in the Big East. "We're trying to really bury our presses, our zone, (because) we're not physical enough," Pitino said. "But if you mix up the defense we can be very effective." Louisville forward Chad Millard, who became sick on the team's trip home from Providence on Saturday, missed his first game of the year.
